 education across Canada engage with issues of diversity and national identity as represented in children’s picture books. Based on research drawn from education courses and student teaching experiences, the book illustrates new and culturally relevant approaches to curricula that meet the needs of increasingly diverse student bodies.The volume focuses on picture books as a central body of texts, drawing on recent reading theory and exploring the implications of bringing the works into school classrooms. Together, the essays offer a unique cross-Canada perspective on how picture books can help students and teachers explore identities, uncover personal and national histories, and locate a sense of place.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aChildren's literature, CanadianxHistory and criticism. 0aPicture books for childrenxEducational aspectszCanada. 0aSchool childrenxBooks and readingzCanada. 4aDISCOUNT-B. 7aEDUCATION / Teaching Methods & Materials / General.2bisacsh1 aBainbridge, Joyce , eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBainbridge, Joyce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrenna, Beverley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurke, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCourtland, Mary Clare, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGonzález, Ismel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHammett, Roberta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnston, Ingrid, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnston, Ingrid, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPhipps, Heather, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShariff